{"id":"2301.08095","submitter":"Alessio Rocci","authors":"Alessio Rocci","title":"Celebrating the birth of De Donder's chemical affinity (1922-2022): from\n  the uncompensated heat to his Ave Maria","comments":"34 pages, 15 figures. Submitted to Foundation of Chemistry","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.hist-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Th\\'eophile De Donder, a Belgian mathematician born in Brussels, elaborated\ntwo important ideas that created a bridge between thermodynamics and chemical\nkinetics. He invented the concept of the degree of advancement of a reaction,\nand, in 1922, he provided a precise mathematical form to the already known\nchemical affinity by translating Clausius's uncompensated heat into formal\nlanguage. These concepts merge in an important inequality that was the starting\npoint for the formalization of out-of-equilibrium thermodynamics. The present\narticle aims to reconstruct how De Donder elaborated his ideas and how he\ndeveloped them by exploring his teaching activity and its connection with his\nscientific production. Furthermore, it emphasizes the role played by the\ndiscussions with his disciples who became his collaborators. The paper analyzes\nDe Donder's efforts in participating in the second Solvay Chemistry Council in\n1925 to call the attention of the international community of chemists. Even if\nhis mathematical approach did not receive much attention at the time, his work\non chemical affinity was the basis for the birth of the so-called Brussels\nschool of thermodynamics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 19 Jan 2023 14:26:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-20"}
