{"id":"2302.00476","submitter":"Frank Wang","authors":"Frank Zhigang Wang","title":"Breaking Landauer bound in a spin-encoded quantum computer","comments":"19 pages, 7 pages","journal-ref":"Springer Nature Quantum Information Processing, 2022","doi":"10.1007/s11128-022-03707-2","report-no":"21, 378 (2022)","categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  It is commonly recognized that the Landauer bound holds in (irreversible)\nquantum measurement. In this study, we overturned this common sense by\nextracting a single spin from a spin spin magnetic interaction experiment to\ndemonstrate that the Landauer bound can be broken quantitatively via quantum\nspin tunneling. It is the quantum limit, rather than the Landauer bound, that\ngoverns the performance of a spin qubit. An optically manipulated spin encoded\nquantum computer is designed, in which energy bound well below the Landauer\nbound to erase a spin qubit at the expense of a long spin relaxation time is\ntheoretically sensible and experimentally verified. This work may represent the\nlast piece of the puzzle in quantum Landauer erasure in terms of a single spin\nbeing the smallest and the closest to the quantum limit.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 18 Jan 2023 18:00:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-02"}
